WEBVTT

00:24.482 --> 00:26.945
Good to see each one of you.

00:27.066 --> 00:28.748
If you have your Bibles, let's pull them out.

00:28.768 --> 00:31.051
We're stepping into our teaching time together today.

00:31.091 --> 00:36.940
And we're going to be in Isaiah 40 as we continue on in our series that we've been in in the book of Isaiah.

00:38.121 --> 00:45.231
One of the most difficult things in life is when, well, when difficult things don't end.

00:48.336 --> 00:52.882
Most can put up with just about anything for a short stint, but

00:53.858 --> 01:00.746
Enduring ongoing chronic trials or discouragement, that's a whole other challenge, right?

01:01.667 --> 01:09.175
Some of you know the challenge is involved in battling, ongoing challenges involved in battling, ongoing health issues, for example.

01:10.197 --> 01:18.386
I mean, it seems like the older I get, it's like one thing after another leads to another, it's like everything's coming apart.

01:20.130 --> 01:25.519
Maybe it's long chapters of heartache that you are enduring in an unhealthy marriage.

01:26.621 --> 01:39.182
Maybe it's prolonged discouragement period that's coming from a negative work situation where you're just stressed with coworkers, always tension in the air.

01:39.222 --> 01:44.210
Some have chronic financial stress and frustration.

01:45.634 --> 01:50.822
It's been said that discouragement usually isn't born in a single bad day.

01:50.882 --> 01:55.469
It's born in the 1,000th day of the same struggle.

01:58.173 --> 02:05.403
When it feels like life is an uphill battle, we can become weary and we can become discouraged.

02:05.463 --> 02:07.847
It simply wears us down over time.

02:08.708 --> 02:12.754
And the longer periods of discouragement go, the more difficult it is to

02:12.898 --> 02:19.885
to try to pop up and stay positive and have hope and have an attitude that's positive.

02:19.906 --> 02:26.793
Imagine hiking with a backpack that someone secretly adds rocks to every mile.

02:30.056 --> 02:34.421
At first you can manage fine, I got this, right?

02:34.461 --> 02:42.770
Then your shoulders start to ache, then you slow down and eventually you wonder if you can keep going at all.

02:43.170 --> 02:51.360
what prolonged hardship feels like, slowly increasing emotional and spiritual weight.

02:53.763 --> 03:00.591
If you find yourself in that type of situation today, then Isaiah has a message for you, and you're gonna be really glad you came to church today.

03:03.014 --> 03:07.419
Message Isaiah brings today as one of those encouraging and refreshing parts of the entire Bible.

03:07.459 --> 03:12.946
Today, Isaiah reminds us that God never, ever, ever forgets us.

03:14.018 --> 03:21.466
In fact, He's committed to renewing us, reviving us and restoring us ultimately.

03:22.047 --> 03:24.970
So if you have your Bibles open to Isaiah 40, let's start there.

03:25.010 --> 03:26.572
Let me start a little context for this first.

03:27.773 --> 03:32.979
In many ways, the book of Isaiah is the Bible in miniature, the Bible in miniature.

03:33.540 --> 03:42.930
Like the Bible, the book has two major divisions and like the Bible, the main theme of the first part is more judgment and the main theme of the second is hope.

03:44.098 --> 03:49.105
So in our study of Isaiah, today chapter 40 begins a whole new section of the book.

03:50.207 --> 04:03.407
Now it's interesting to note that the historical time context for Isaiah 40 through the end, 40 through 66, it's an entirely different timeframe than the first 39 chapters.

04:05.470 --> 04:10.898
As chapter 40 opens, it's addressing issues that happened about 300 years after chapter 39.

04:12.770 --> 04:14.992
Obviously Isaiah was not alive then.

04:15.032 --> 04:35.853
Scholars have offered different explanations for this, but to me the best explanation is that God has given, divinely given, Isaiah the ability to see into the future and speak to the hearts of those who will live through the coming decimation and exile of Judah at the hands of the Babylonians in 586 BC.

04:37.074 --> 04:40.978
Bottom line, here's what I want you to hold on and it hold into your brains.

04:41.410 --> 04:52.990
As we come to Isaiah 40, Isaiah is addressing a people who will become very familiar with hardship, discouragement, prolonged challenges in their lives.

04:54.092 --> 04:55.534
But Isaiah is assuring them.

04:55.795 --> 04:58.619
God has not forgotten you and he has not abandoned you.

04:59.240 --> 05:00.883
Your restoration is coming.

05:02.306 --> 05:07.154
This message was as vital for them in those days as it is for us in our day.

05:08.674 --> 05:16.063
As you remember, from the first half of our series, Isaiah one to 39 was very heavy on warning and judgment.

05:17.164 --> 05:22.891
It emphasized God as holy and just, worthy of obedience.

05:22.911 --> 05:32.683
But now, beginning with Isaiah 40, the prophecy shifts to consolation, to hope, promise, and God as redeemer and comforter.

05:33.964 --> 05:35.506
It's a great day to be in church.

05:38.242 --> 05:40.465
Let's start in chapter 40 verse one.

05:41.807 --> 05:42.828
Get ourselves started.

05:42.848 --> 05:46.874
Isaiah writes, comfort, comfort my people, says your God.

05:48.016 --> 05:59.412
Speak tenderly to Jerusalem and proclaim to her that her hard service has been completed, that her sin has been paid for, and she has received from the Lord's hand double for all her sins.

06:00.493 --> 06:06.802
A voice of one calling, a voice of one calling in the wilderness, prepare

06:07.234 --> 06:08.796
the way for the Lord.

06:08.896 --> 06:12.000
Make straight in the desert a highway for our God.

06:12.781 --> 06:19.570
Every valley shall be raised up, every mountain and hill made low, the rough ground should become level, the rugged places a plain.

06:20.651 --> 06:27.860
And the glory of the Lord will be revealed and all the people will see it together for the mouth of the Lord has spoken in.

06:29.021 --> 06:35.890
Comfort in Hebrew means to turn away suffering, either by ending the suffering

06:35.970 --> 06:41.235
taking the suffering away, or by coming alongside and helping a person through it.

06:42.757 --> 06:47.181
Once God calls out to comfort his people, friends, it's as good as done.

06:48.502 --> 06:52.446
The repetition of comfort indicates urgency.

06:54.028 --> 07:04.658
To be certain, the exile will bring tremendous suffering on his people, but now he's saying, when their suffering comes to an end, when it's complete, when their discipline is over,

07:05.346 --> 07:09.031
When they have endured double trouble for all their sins, now it's restoration time.

07:10.072 --> 07:11.614
Now it's restoration time.

07:15.018 --> 07:19.484
Comfort, tender care, renewal is coming.

07:21.446 --> 07:31.058
The restoration starts with a declaration that one is coming who will fully resolve their sin issues and lead them back to their God.

07:31.682 --> 07:40.891
They will recognize this Savior who's coming because one will precede him and will continue to prepare a way for the deliverer.

07:41.612 --> 07:44.615
Then the text says, the glory of the Lord will be revealed.

07:45.496 --> 07:46.156
Sound familiar?

07:46.176 --> 07:49.039
Some of you, huh?

07:49.059 --> 07:59.049
These verses might sound familiar because all four gospel writers use them to refer to the ministry of John the Baptist and introduce the ministry of John the Baptist.

07:59.069 --> 08:00.210
In fact, in John,

08:00.514 --> 08:05.840
